  "opinion": "As a curious woman who’s spent years listening to my children’s questions about the world, I’ve come to understand stereotype threat in STEM not as a distant academic concept but as something that echoes in the quiet moments of my own life. Growing up in a neighborhood where many of my peers didn’t have the same opportunities to explore science, I remember feeling a subtle pressure to prove myself—especially when I’d see my friends struggling with math or physics. Stereotype threat isn’t just about being labeled; it’s about the internalized fear that your group’s success is tied to your individual performance, which can make learning feel like a battle rather than a discovery. In my community, where many families didn’t have access to advanced education, this pressure was real. For example, when my son asked me why girls can’t be engineers, I realized how deeply these stereotypes can shape children’s self-perception. We should address stereotype threat in STEM not with grand, top-down policies but with small, meaningful actions that empower individuals to see themselves as capable. In Los Angeles, where I live, I’ve seen schools start to incorporate storytelling about diverse scientists to show that everyone has a place in STEM. This kind of approach, rooted in empathy and community, helps students feel seen and valued. It’s not about fixing a problem but about fostering an environment where curiosity, not fear, drives learning. As someone who’s spent hours on social media listening to conversations about education, I’ve learned that addressing stereotype threat requires listening first—then acting with care and intention.",
